geuk am Beispiel von Brechts Der kaukasische Kreidekreis -- tBertolt Brecht und der chinesische Schauspieler Mei Lanfang -- t“Living Drafts”: Brecht’s Poetics of Exile in “Garden in progress” -- tBook Reviews -- tAnja Hartl. Brecht and Post-1990s British Drama. Dialectical Theatre Today -- tElisabeth Tropper. Enter the Ghosts of Europe. Heimsuchungen Europas im Theater der Gegenwart -- tJonathan Wipplinger. The Jazz Republic: Music, Race, and American Culture in Weimer Germany; Mark Christian Thompson. Anti-Music: Jazz and Racial Blackness in German Thought Between the Wars -- tLydia J. White. Theater des Exils: Bertolt Brechts “Der Messingkauf” -- tDr. Prateek. Brecht in India. The Poetics and Politics of Transcultural Theatre -- tMelanie Reichert. Kultur in Stücken: Barthes, Brecht, Artaud -- tFlorian Vaßen. “einfach zerschmeißen.” Brecht-Material: Lyrik–Prosa–Theater–Lehrstück. Mit einem Blick auf Heiner Müller -- tNotes on the Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn annual volume, this time with special attention to the relevance of Brecht's work in today's world of resurgent authoritarianism and the need for resistance.The Brecht Yearbook is the central scholarly forum for discussion of Brecht's life and work and of topics of particular interest to him, especially the politics of literature and of theater in a global context. Embracing a wide variety of perspectives and approaches, like Brecht himself it is committed to the use value of literature, theater, and theory. Volume 47 features the special section "Brecht Post-2020: Fascism and Misinformation, Resistance and Intersectionality," with articles on Fear and Misery of the Third Reich and today's surge in autocracy, on an adaptation of The Measures Taken and Brazil's right-wing turn, on Brecht's exile poetry as a model for truth in an era of fake news, and on the relevance of Brecht's late-1940s adaptations of plays about resistance, among others. Varied new research on Brecht follows: essays on the 1919 Spartacist uprising's influence on Drums in the Night, on the anti-Stalinist critique in the prologue to The Caucasian Chalk Circle, on a recent Korean production of the same play in traditional Changgeuk style, and on Mei Lanfang's performances in Moscow in 1935 that Brecht most likely attended. The final essay considers Brecht's unfinished exile poem "Garden in progress" and the inherent incompletion of artworks and historical processes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern Literature. 7aDRAMA / European / German.2bisacsh  aAuthoritarianism.  aAutocracy.  aChanggeuk style.  aDrums in the Night.  aExile Poetry.  aFascism.  aFear and Misery of the Third Reich.  aGarden in Progress.  aIntersectionality.  aMei Lanfang.  aThe Caucasian Chalk Circle.  aThe Measures Taken.1 aBarnett, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhatawadekar, Sai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEarle Gurganus, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGier, Helmut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGurganus, Albert Earle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartl, Anja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHee Lee, Eun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeld, Phoebe von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHillesheim, Jurgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHillesheim, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Lesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab